To make a program case-sensitive, we need to ensure that the comparison of strings is done in a way that acknowledges the difference between uppercase and lowercase characters. In Python, strings are naturally case-sensitive, meaning that "hello" is not equal to "Hello". 

So, if you want to implement a case-sensitive program, you don't need to make any specific changes. However, if you're working with a programming language that doesn't inherently handle case sensitivity (like Java), you can use specific strings methods to compare strings case-sensitively. For instance, in Java, you can use the `equalsIgnoreCase()` method to ignore the case of characters during comparison. But if you want to compare strings case-sensitively, you'd need to manually convert the strings to a case-sensitive format. 

Here is an example of a case-sensitive program in Java:

```java
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String str1 = "hello";
        String str2 = "Hello";

        // Check if the strings are equal without considering case
        if (str1.equalsIgnoreCase(str2)) {
            System.out.println("The strings are equal");
        } else {
            System.out.println("The strings are not equal");
        }

        // Check if the strings are equal without case conversion
        if (str1.equals(str2.toLowerCase())) {
            System.out.println("The strings are equal");
        } else {
            System.out.println("The strings are not equal");
        }
    }
}
```

In this example, the first `if` statement will print "The strings are equal" because the `equalsIgnoreCase()` method ignores case during the comparison. The second `if` statement will also print "The strings are equal" because `toLowerCase()` converts the string to lowercase, making it possible for the strings to be equal even though they have different case.

