To update an Angular application to run change detection only on specified components, you can either use the `OnPush` change detection strategy or manually trigger the change detection. To make things more efficient, try to use the `OnPush` strategy wherever possible, as it performs better.

1. Using `OnPush` change detection strategy:

The `OnPush` change detection strategy allows Angular to check a component only when its input properties change, or when an event is triggered inside the component. To implement this strategy, set the `changeDetection` property of your component to `ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush`.

Here's an example:

```typescript
import { Component, Input, ChangeDetectionStrategy } from '@angular/core';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-my-component',
  templateUrl: './my-component.component.html',
  styleUrls: ['./my-component.component.scss'],
  changeDetection: ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush
})
export class MyComponent {
  @Input() someInputData: any;

  // Your component logic here
}
```

When using the `OnPush` strategy, be aware that Angular will only update the view when the input properties get a new reference, not when the data inside them is changed. Therefore, it's a good practice to use immutable objects for your inputs.

2. Manually triggering change detection:

If you need more control over when Angular runs change detection, you can also trigger this process manually. Firstly, inject `ChangeDetectorRef` into your component:

```typescript
import { Component, ChangeDetectorRef } from '@angular/core';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-my-component',
  templateUrl: './my-component.component.html',
  styleUrls: ['./my-component.component.scss']
})
export class MyComponent {
  constructor(private cdr: ChangeDetectorRef) { }

  // Your component logic here
}
```

Then, call the `detectChanges()` method on the `ChangeDetectorRef` instance to manually run change detection:

```typescript
this.cdr.detectChanges();
```

Call this method whenever you want to let Angular know that it should update the view. However, use this method sparingly and only when absolutely needed, as it could affect the performance of your application.

